ssed physical and racial boundaries—from black to white, South to North, and rural to urban—and how they found expression for these movements in the insistent music they were creating.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBig band musicxSocial aspects. 0aJazz musiciansxHomes and hauntsxUnited States. 0aJazz musiciansxHomes and hauntszUnited States. 0aMusic and racexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aMusic and racezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  ajazz, america, music, history, venues, concerts, improvisation, nation, identity, performance, race, geography, boundaries, jan garber, duke ellington, bandleader, saxophone, charlie barnet, guitar, christian, segregation, south, north, traveling, jim crow, civil rights, prejudice, catalina island, manhattan, oklahoma city, musicians, big band, casino ballroom, make believe, meadowbrook inn, orchestra, region, place, space, nonfiction, reference.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226044965423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226044965/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles